<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Bathory</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-06-29 18:35:24</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>i tested the proc on the Zealot's sword several times one night, this is what i found:<BR>
<BR>
Soul Bond: Lasts for 30 seconds<BR>
Life taps 14HP per tick for 5 ticks for total of 70HP. (The actual HP gained per tick was 16HP, but i subtracted the 2HP i get naturally per tick while standing.)<BR>
<BR>
I tried to test its stackablility with itself. It was very difficult since i was in actual combat and taking hits, so my tests arent done on this part of it yet.<BR>
Here is a brief snipet of what i noticed in regards to multi-procs:<BR>
<BR>
The first proc(proc1)went thru 1 tick (tick1)before the second proc, for 16HP/tick (remember 2HP of that is not the proc, but my natural HP regen while standing).<BR>
<BR>
Heres where it gets weird, and possibly very ugly.<BR>
<BR>
When the next proc (proc2) went off, the next tick (tick2)was 6HP (not a typo), tick3 was 11HP, tick4 was 11HP, tick5 was 6HP (again, no typo) , and tick6 back to 16HP (presumably because proc1 wore off).<BR>
<BR>
Now at least according to what i saw here, when its stacked, it actullay does LESS DMG during that time period per tick, than on a single proc. That, of course, makes no sense at all. If if doesnt stack onto itself (meaning 30/tick --16+14-- during the stacked time) it should at least renew itself. it would still be 16/tick, but reset the 30 second timer.<BR>
<BR>
when i have the chance, i will do a more controled multi-proc test on this. Looks like when the nerfed the proc, they bugged it as well. <BR>
<BR>
Now i will mention that i REALLY hope that im wrong here :) and that my future tests prove differently than what i have seen here in regards to multi-procs.</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Bathory D'Allatu</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-07-06 17:17:11</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>OK:<BR>
After paying closer attention to the HP gained per tick, this is what i noticed.<BR>
Tick 1 = 6HP<BR>
Tick 2 = 11HP<BR>
Tick 3 = 16HP<BR>
Tick 4 = 21HP<BR>
Tick 5 = 26HP<BR>
<BR>
For some reason, instead of the same amount of HP being gained per tick, it goes up 5HP each tick, until it reaches its max at 80HP (10HP of that is my natural 2HP per tick while standing, as mentioned before).<BR>
<BR>
So kinda bizarre.<BR>
<BR>
As for stacking: It doe not stack on itself (i suppose that was a pipedream), it renews itself like most other DOTs.<BR>
<BR>
So depending on when your second proc is, determines how much you actually benefit.<BR>
<BR>
The sooner the second proc, the less HP you get , since the first couple ticks are really low HP-wise. And when it procs twice on a double-attack, its worthless, since it didnt even make it to Tick 1 for the initial 6HP gain.<BR>
<BR>
So the proc is totally inferior to that of Soul Leeches. But again, the DMG/DLY ratio rules SL's. So i opt to stay with the Zealot Sword. But would toss it aside for the Inlaid Jade Crescent Axe without hesitation. Even the Deathbringers Rod is a consideration ,which i turned down for the Zealot's thinking that it had the 350 proc :( . But oh well, at least it looks really cool.<BR>
<BR>
I am curious to know if the Soul Bond on the Soulbinder is the same or not though.</font></td></tr></table>
